04591nam a22006255i 9780822388821DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223888217 a10.1515/97808223888212doi  a(DE-B1597)554123  a(OCoLC)1224278363  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aR836b.H46 2008 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a610.9511 aHeinrich, Ari Larissa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Afterlife of Images :bTranslating the Pathological Body between China and the West /cAri Larissa Heinrich; Judith Farquhar, Arjun Appadurai. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b42 illustrations, incl. 8 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBody, Commodity, Text00tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. How China Became the "Cradle of Smallpox" -- t2. The Pathological Body -- t3. The Pathological Empire -- t4. "What's Hard for the Eye to See" -- tEpilogue: Through the Microscope -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1739 China's emperor authorized the publication of a medical text that included images of children with smallpox to aid in the diagnosis and treatment of the disease. Those images made their way to Europe, where they were interpreted as indicative of the ill health and medical backwardness of the Chinese. In the mid-nineteenth century, the celebrated Cantonese painter Lam Qua collaborated with the American medical missionary Peter Parker in the creation of portraits of Chinese patients with disfiguring pathologies, rendered both before and after surgery. Europeans saw those portraits as evidence of Western medical prowess. Within China, the visual idiom that the paintings established influenced the development of medical photography. In The Afterlife of Images, Ari Larissa Heinrich investigates the creation and circulation of Western medical discourses that linked ideas about disease to Chinese identity beginning in the eighteenth century.Combining literary studies, the history of science, and visual culture studies, Heinrich analyzes the rhetoric and iconography through which medical missionaries transmitted to the West an image of China as "sick" or "diseased." He also examines the absorption of that image back into China through missionary activity, through the earliest translations of Western medical texts into Chinese, and even through the literature of Chinese nationalism. Heinrich argues that over time "scientific" Western representations of the Chinese body and culture accumulated a host of secondary meanings, taking on an afterlife with lasting consequences for conceptions of Chinese identity in China and beyond its borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aMedical illustrationxHistory. 0aMedical illustrationzChinaxHistory. 0aMedicine in artxHistory. 0aMedicine in artzChinaxHistory. 0aMedicinezChinaxHistory. 0aMissions, MedicalzChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aAppadurai, Arjun, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarquhar, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388821zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388821423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388821.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles